quest_title: The motor of an electric train can give it an acceleration of 1 m/s\({}^{2}\) & brakes can give a negative acceleration of 3m/s\({}^{2}\) . The shortest time is which the train can make a trip between two stations 1215 m apart is
explanation_txt:
For acceleration

\(\begin{array}{l}{S_{1}=\cfrac{1}{2} a t^{2}=\cfrac{1}{2} \times 1 \times t^{2}=\cfrac{t^{2}}{2}} \\ {V_{1}=a t=t}\end{array}\)

For retardation

\(\begin{array}{l}{\mathrm{u}=\mathrm{t}} \\ {v=0} \\ {\mathrm{V}=\mathrm{u}+\mathrm{a}^{1} \mathrm{t}^{\prime}} \\ {0=\mathrm{t}-3 \mathrm{t}^{\prime}} \\ {\mathrm{t}=3 \mathrm{t}^{\prime}}\end{array}\)

\(\begin{aligned} \mathrm{S}_{2} &=\mathrm{u.t}^{\prime}+\cfrac{1}{2} \mathrm{a}^{1} \mathrm{t}^{\prime 2} \\ &=\mathrm{t} \mathrm{t}^{\prime}-\cfrac{1}{2} \times 3 \mathrm{t}^{\prime 2} \\ &=3 \mathrm{t}^{\prime 2}-1.5 \mathrm{t}^{2} \\ &=1.5 \mathrm{t}^{2} \end{aligned}\)

Now,

\(\begin{array}{l}{\mathrm{S}_{1}+\mathrm{S}_{2}=1215} \\ {4.5 \mathrm{t}^{2}+1.5 \mathrm{t}^{12}=1215} \\ {\mathrm{t}^{1}=\sqrt{\cfrac{1215}{6}}=14.2 \mathrm{sec}}\end{array}\)

\(\begin{aligned} \therefore \mathrm{T}=\mathrm{t}+\mathrm{t}^{1} &=3 \times 14.2+14.2 \\ &=56.8 \mathrm{sec} \end{aligned}\)

Alternative Method

\(\begin{array}{l}{\mathrm{s}=\cfrac{t^{2}}{2}\left(\cfrac{a_{1} a_{2}}{a_{1}+a_{2}}\right)} \\ {\text { or, } \mathrm{t}^{2}=\cfrac{2 s\left(a_{1}+a_{2}\right)}{a_{1} a_{2}}}\end{array}\)

\(\text { or, } \mathrm{t}=\sqrt{\cfrac{2 \mathrm{s}\left(\mathrm{a}_{1}+\mathrm{a}_{2}\right)}{\mathrm{a}_{1} \mathrm{a}_{2}}}=\sqrt{\cfrac{2 \times 1215(1+3)}{1 \times 3}}\)

\(=56.9 \mathrm{sec}\)

quest_title: Area bounded by the curve \(x^{2} =4y\) and the straight line \(x=4y-2\) is :
explanation_txt:
The given curves are:

\( y = \cfrac{x^2}{4} \\ y = \cfrac{x}{4} + \cfrac{1}{2} \)

The points of intersection are:

\[ \cfrac{x^2}{4} = \cfrac{x}{4} + \cfrac{1}{2} \]

\[ \Rightarrow x^2 - x - 2 = 0 \]

\[ \Rightarrow x = \cfrac{1 \pm 3}{2} = 2,-1 \]

So, the required area is:

\[ A = \left| \int_{-1}^{2} \left[\cfrac{x^2}{4} - \cfrac{x}{4} - \cfrac{1}{2} \right] dx \right| = \cfrac{9}{8} \]
